In the present model the new resonance being responsible for the observed diphoton excess 
is a pseudoscalar and at the same time plays the role of the mediator 
between SM particles and the DM particle.
Having introduced two effective operators of dimension five, the DM annihilation channels
are now $\chi \chi \to W^+ W^-, Z Z, h h, \bar f f, \gamma \gamma, gg$. 
SM fermions are denoted by $f$. One question that we would like to address here is 
if there can be viable regions in the DM sector which is consistent with the expected 
resonance of mass $\sim 750$ GeV and decay width of $\sim 45$ GeV.  
We fix the UV scale as $\Lambda = 10$ TeV and perform our computations 
for two sets of the effective couplings as $\lambda_{g} = \lambda_{\gamma} = 0.2$ 
and $\lambda_{g} = 3 \lambda_{\gamma} = 0.6$. 
We pointed out earlier that the resonance decay into a pair of DM,  
dominants its total decay width. Therefore, the total width is much sensitive 
to two parameters $m_{\text{DM}}$ and $g_{\chi}$, in particular when $m_{\text{DM}} \sim m_{\rho}/2$.   
To do the DM phenomenology we implement our model into the program MicrOMEGAs \cite{Belanger:2013oya}.
We then study the dependency of the viable parameter space to the mixing angle, respecting the 
WMAP and Planck bounds on the relic density \cite{Ade:2013zuv,Hinshaw:2012aka} and the early LHC-13TeV expected range for 
the resonance decay width $\Gamma^{\text{tot}}/m_{\rho} \sim 0.03-0.06$.  
Our numerical results for the set $\lambda_{g} = \lambda_{\gamma} = 0.2$ are shown 
in Figs.~\ref{relic-width1}, \ref{relic-width2} and \ref{relic-width3} for various values of the 
mixing angle for DM mass in the range $50$ GeV up to $500$ GeV. 
It is evident from the figures  the role of the 
mixing angle is quite subtle in finding the DM mass range which gives both the relic density
and the resonance decay width correctly. Almost independent of the mixing angle, the correct decay 
width is obtained for $g_{\chi} \sim 1$. 
For quite large mixing angle, i.e., $\sin \theta = 0.5$, there is 
no DM candidate with $g_{\chi} \sim 1$ since now the annihilation cross section 
favors small values of the coupling to give the correct relic density.  
On the other side, for smaller values of the mixing angle there can always be found a viable DM 
mass which starts from $\sim 80$ GeV up to $\sim 300$ GeV with decreasing the mixing angle.  
Our findings for the set $\lambda_{g} = 3 \lambda_{\gamma} = 0.6$ are illustrated 
in Figs.~\ref{relic-width4}, \ref{relic-width4} and \ref{relic-width5}.
It can be seen readily that our results do not change much by increasing $\lambda_{g}$.

Assuming that a resonance underlies the observed excess, the diphoton signal 
cross section is given by $\sigma_{\gamma\gamma} \sim \sigma(\text{pp} \to \rho) \text{Br}(\rho \to \gamma \gamma)$.
To compute the pseudoscalar production cross section we first implement our 
model into FeynRules \cite{Alloul:2013bka} and then into MadGraph5 \cite{Alwall:2011uj}. 
Since the decay rate of the resonance into diphoton is mainly governed by 
the effective interaction, we employ the 
relation $\Gamma_{\gamma} \sim \frac{m_{\rho}^3}{\pi} (\frac{\lambda_{\gamma}}{\Lambda})^2 \cos^2 \theta$.      
The numerical predictions for the signal cross section are presented in Table.~\ref{numerics} 
for six benchmark points, taking two different values for the gloun effective coupling as
$\lambda_{g} = 0.2$ and $0.6$. We realize that for $\lambda_{g} \gtrsim 0.2$ it is possible to explain
the diphoton excess for DM masses in the range $\sim 88-280$ GeV.   




